metadata.name: Tumble Down Light Factory #68
metadata.description:
Tumble Down Light Factory is an interpretation of light installations & murals.

It attempts to trigger the feeling of coming up on a new block in a new city to discover an unexpected piece of art that is stories tall or entering a new room, knowing there will be a projection dominating the space with its light and color.

This is an abstract distillation of those things and those feelings.

Each composition is initially drawn to a hidden “template” canvas which is sampled and then rendered on the main canvas in various ways after applying some transforms to give it some depth (and so you can actually see it.)

Viewing in full-screen is nice. You should try it.

T : Save hidden ‘template’ image
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution

metadata.name: Lush Fields  #17
metadata.description:
* fixed version * 

Lush Fields puts you in a space far from home,fluffy,lush grass under you ... and lots of space in front of you.

Lush Fields was created as an offshoot from upcoming works, because the minimalistic focus on the grass, light and brushy haptics has a charm on its own.

Still there are lots of parameters which can change.. colours, direction of light, positions, variety
 Of the ground modulations etc.

I hope you have a good mint .. and if you are not satisfied: try another one :)

metadata.name: Ongemak #77
metadata.description:
Wabi-sabi (侘寂): appreciate impermanence and imperfection

There is little chance of a 'perfect' work of art. The small imperfections require reflection. 

The variation and randomness give the work some asymmetry, common in wabi-sabi esthetics. Because of a limited color palette and the simple shapes used, the works keep their simplicity (another principle of wabi-sabi). The noisy texture gives it some roughness, indeed again a core principle of wabi-sabi. 

The colors are reminiscent of the 70s and 80s. Some think that everything was better in the past. The trick is to enjoy the moment.

Thinking about impermanence is sometimes uncomfortable, 'ongemak' in Dutch, but also valuable.

metadata.name: square haze [86] #73
metadata.description:
Finally it is! Another one piece from square haze collection. This time it is generative fxhash item that represents aesthetics compilation found during previous pieces research on hic et nunc with some improvements discovered during fxhash adaptation. There are some features that controls generated token appearance:
- squareMode: different settings that determine algorithms used to create piece
- colorTheme: one of the best color palettes from the internet
- colorPicker: function used to select color schemes for grid mode
- grid: amount of splits in master square
- colorShift: step that determines how colors iterated in sub-squares (doesn't affect black and white squares)
- padding: yes
- bgIndex: sometimes it adds some vibe to the whole image
- isSiblings: probably the most awful part of the internal that looks great
- law: as it is normal or uniform, the hash will choose
- noiseChance: probability of new created square to became noisy one
- patternChance: the same as noise but with patttterns
- spread: something like dispersion for normal distribution I suppose
- border: minimal distance between squares
- minSize: minimal square size
- roundness: oh, this was accidental and fun, so it is included

There will be more.
Probably #87, #88, #89, #90 and #91
No ETA, no promises, don't know what differences will bring the future, but believing in the best.

27 May 2022 // NEURAL HAZE

metadata.description:
Generative visual composition, hybrid techniques, interactive, textures source created with GAN, assist by AI, eclectic, colors, transform in autonomous system, glitch, made with code, and modular patch.
